{"actual_usd":0.15861,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":189,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31155,"reply":"\"To the Father.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, buying half a second because I want to answer cleanly, not slickly.* \"Not in the sense of a little stage trick where God is pretending to have two parts. Christians mean one God, three persons — Father, Son, Holy Spirit — so in Gethsemane the Son is really praying to the Father.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"And because Jesus took real human nature, that prayer is also a real human prayer — obedience under agony, not theater. If you flatten the Trinity, yeah, it sounds like God talking to himself. If you keep both claims — Jesus truly God, Jesus truly man, and the Father not the Son — it lands more like divine fellowship and filial obedience than self-address.\"\n\n\"What part feels hardest to believe — the Trinity part, or the two-natures part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":33.49229500000003,"run_id":"f86dee2a-0d0e-4cbc-9600-fcc6bad9f554"}
